Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Access Bank; Zenith Bank of Nigeria

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-08T15:32:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-access-bank-zenith-bank-of-nigeria.html
Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
slumped for a 10th day, the longest losing streak since at least
January 2004, dropping 3.1 percent to 739.85 by the 4 p.m. close
in Windhoek to the lowest closing level since August 2010.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index retreated for a
fifth consecutive day, falling 1.9 percent to 22,963.11 by the
2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed statement
from the exchange. Kenya’s All-Share Index declined for a second
day, dropping 1.5 percent to 65.14 by the 3 p.m. close in
Nairobi, the lowest close since March 5, 2010. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index snapped four days of gains, slipping
0.9 percent to 1,175.19 by the 3 p.m. close in Accra.
Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for second day, weakening 2.8
percent to 1,942.66 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis , the
lowest close since March 18.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Zenith Bank Plc (ZENITHBA)  ,  Nigeria ’s biggest lender by
market value, lost 67 kobo, or 4.9 percent, to 12.92 naira, the
lowest price since Sept. 30, after the central bank nationalized
Afribank Plc, Bank PHB Plc and Spring Bank Plc, institutions
that were deemed unlikely to meet a Sept. 30 deadline to
recapitalize.  Guaranty Trust Bank Plc (GUARANTY)  , the second-biggest
lender, declined 66 kobo, or 5 percent, to 12.59 naira, the
lowest close since Nov. 30.  Access Bank Plc (ACCESS)  , the
fifth largest bank, fell 33 kobo, or 5 percent, to 6.27 naira,
the biggest drop since Aug. 3, 2010.  To contact the reporter on this story:
